# Reply Memory Feature

## Overview

The reply memory system improves future draft replies from prior user corrections.

It does two jobs:

- act as a lightweight runtime corrective layer for drafting
- automatically build useful knowledge for users who do not maintain a manual knowledge base

The system does not treat all learned data the same way.
Some learned items are always-on writing preferences.
Some are conditional facts or procedures.
Some are raw draft/send correction signals on `ReplyMemorySource`, plus short-lived sent-text evidence on `DraftSendLog`, which stay useful for analysis and debugging but are not injected directly into prompts.

## Core Principles

### Atomic Memories

Each memory should be one atomic fragment in a single canonical `content` field.

The memory itself should already be a prompt-ready instruction or fact.

### Memory Types

The current system uses these conceptual types:

- `fact`
  - durable business knowledge, routing rules, pricing, policies
- `preference`
  - writing style, formatting, greeting/sign-off habits
- `procedure`
  - how to handle a recurring class of replies
- raw evidence
  - draft/send correction signals used for analysis, consolidation, and evals

### Small Prompt Footprint

The drafting prompt stays small.

- style/preferences should be compact and mostly always-on
- facts/procedures should be selected conditionally
- raw evidence should usually stay out of the prompt

## Retrieval Model

### Main Drafter

The main drafting path should receive:

- manual writing style
- learned style profile
- a small selected set of relevant facts/procedures

It does not rely on a large memory dump.

## Knowledge Base Relationship

Most users do not have a manual knowledge base.

The reply memory system can serve as an automatic KB for those users.

That means:

- `fact` and `procedure` items are effectively auto-KB entries
- `preference` items are user-specific drafting bias
- raw evidence is the learning substrate that feeds both

The system does not assume manual KB coverage.

## Evidence and Retention

Raw draft/send evidence is useful for:

- improving prompts
- consolidating memories
- validating conflicts

Temporary retention is acceptable, and the current system:

- keeps raw sent-text evidence for about a week
- lazily cleans it up when reply-memory sync runs
- keeps durable memories longer than raw evidence

## Current Implementation Notes

- `ReplyMemory` stores one canonical `content` field plus `kind`, `scopeType`, and `scopeValue`
- promptable memories are `fact` and `procedure`
- `preference` memories are account-level and feed learned writing style
- learned writing style is stored separately on `EmailAccount`
- raw evidence lives on `ReplyMemorySource` and keeps draft/send examples for short-term analysis

## Future Notes

Potential follow-up ideas:

- subagent memory CAG with tag-based progressive disclosure and optional free-form search
- better conflict handling through reinforcement, recency, and stale-memory detection
- stronger analysis and eval generation from repeated residual draft mistakes

Key files:

- `apps/web/prisma/schema.prisma`
- `apps/web/utils/ai/reply/extract-reply-memories.ts`
- `apps/web/utils/ai/reply/reply-memory.ts`
- `apps/web/utils/ai/reply/summarize-learned-writing-style.ts`

## Key Design Rule

The memory system is a residual improvement layer.

Search, inbox context, relationships, and KB retrieval should continue to do most of the factual heavy lifting.
Memory should capture what repeatedly goes wrong or what the user reliably corrects.
